<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-807-506  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 807 506.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Sept 3 1990 v12 n36 p48(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple, the courts wonder: Who owns the desktop metaphor? ('lookand feel' issues) (State of the Industry) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Parker, Rachel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Apple continues to resist attempts to limit its allegations thatthe Microsoft Windows and HP NewWave graphical images violate itscopyrights on Macintosh 'look and feel,' with officials repeatedlyrefusing to define which specific features are infringed upon.andP;  Anewly appointed judge asked Apple for a firm definition at ahearing in Aug 1990, and lead Apple counsel Jack Brown awkwardlydescribed the graphical interface and 'desktop metaphor' as theheart of the Macintosh.andP;  Brown states that competitors have almostlimitless alternative methods of representing an officeenvironment that would not violate Apple copyrights, but Applecannot expect to claim sole ownership of such images as cardfiles, file folders, pencils, and other business images becausethese are extremely common in both computerized andnon-computerized environments.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (cases).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (legal aspects).andO;Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceLegal IssuesComputer IndustryTrends.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>